[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/new_minor_forcing"]
[Student "S"]
{This 14 point hand is almost good enough to open 1NT, but you bid 1\D. Partner responds 1\H.  

You could bid either 1NT or 2\C. You decide on 1NT.

Partner says 2\C.  

This is NMF, asking if you have 3 \Hs. You only have 2, but you have a great notrump hand now. Since partner must have at least invitational strength you jump right to 3NT.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "5"]
[Dealer "S"]
[Vulnerable "NS"]
[Deal "S:QT5.JT.AK642.Q86 AJ8.Q987.QT973.T K94.AK542.85.KJ9 7632.63.J.A75432"]
[Declarer "S"]
[Contract "3NT"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "S"]
1D pass 1H pass 1NT pass 2C pass 2NT pass 3NT pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 5, chOption: S, chBasis: N, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:2, nBasis: 0, nRot: 2, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "6266fb4ec4e08d678f9653e1e4fea493541795d0e4bba774b44a5d08a8b78bbd"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/new_minor_forcing"]
[Student "S"]
{With 15 points you are going to insist on game. First you respond 1\H. Partner rebids 1NT. What do you say next? 

Partner has 12-14 points, balanced. You are happy with notrump, but would prefer to play in \Hs if partner has three cards in the suit. To find out if he does, use New Minor Forcing.

So you say 2\C and partner replies 2NT. It is your bid again. 

Partner doesn't have 3 \Hs. That's what you wanted to know, you bid 3NT.}

